#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/COO/diana/skills/marketplace/lean-startup/references/five-whys.md
M|references|The Five Whys is a root cause analysis technique adapted from the Toyota prd System for use in startups. When something goes wrong, most teams fix the symptom and move on. The Five Whys forces you to 
M|references|When a problem occurs, ask "why" five times. Each answer becomes the basis for the next question. By the fifth "why," you typically arrive at a root cause that is systemic, not situational.
M|references|**The insight:** Surface problems are symptoms of deeper process failures. Fixing symptoms leads to recurring problems. Fixing root causes prevents entire categories of future problems.
M|references|State the problem as a specific, observable event. Not "the product has bugs" but "Customer X received an incorrect invoice on Tuesday."
M|references|**Good problem statements:**
M|references|- "Three customers reported receiving duplicate emails on March 15"
M|references|- "The deploy on Friday caused a 2-hour outage for all users"
M|references|- "New user onboarding completion dropped from 65% to 40% this week"
M|references|**Bad problem statements:**
M|references|- "Our quality is poor" (too vague)
M|references|- "Users are unhappy" (too broad)
M|references|- "Things are broken" (not specific)
M|references|Include everyone directly involved in the problem. Not managers looking over shoulders, but the people who touched the code, the process, or the customer interaction.
M|references|**Who to include:**
M|references|- The person who discovered the problem
M|references|- The person(s) who contributed to the problem
M|references|- A facilitator (someone not directly involved)
M|references|- Optionally, one person with organizational ctx (can explain process history)
M|references|**Who not to include:**
M|references|- Senior leaders who will inhibit honest answers
M|references|- People looking to assign blame
M|references|- Anyone not directly connected to the incident
M|references|Work through the chain, ensuring each "why" is answered with a factual, verifiable statement.
M|references|For each level of "why," make an investment in prevention that is proportional to the severity. Small problems get small fixes. Recurring problems get larger systemic changes.
M|references|Each investment gets an owner and a deadline. Follow up in the next cycle.
M|references|**Problem:** Friday deploy caused a 2-hour outage for all users.
M|references|| Level | Question | Answer |
M|references||-------|----------|--------|
M|references|| Why 1 | Why did the deploy cause an outage? | A database migration script failed halfway through, leaving the schema in an inconsistent state. |
M|references|| Why 2 | Why did the migration script fail? | It timed out because the users table has 2 million rows and the script added an index without a timeout setting. |
M|references|| Why 3 | Why was there no timeout setting? | The developer was not aware that large table migrations need special handling. |
M|references|| Why 4 | Why was the developer not aware? | There is no documentation or checklist for database migrations in the team. |
M|references|| Why 5 | Why is there no migration checklist? | We have never formalized our dpl process; it has been tribal knw. |
M|references|**Proportional investments:**
M|references|| Level | Investment | Effort | Owner | Deadline |
M|references||-------|-----------|--------|-------|----------|
M|references|| 1 | Fix the specific migration and restore service | 2 hours | DevOps lead | Immediate |
M|references|| 2 | Add timeout settings to migration runner | 1 hour | Backend dev | This week |
M|references|| 3 | Create migration best practices doc | 4 hours | Senior dev | Next week |
M|references|| 4 | Add migration checklist to PR rv template | 2 hours | Tech lead | Next week |
M|references|| 5 | Schedule monthly "process gap" reviews | 1 hour/month | Engineering manager | Ongoing |
M|references|**Problem:** Monthly churn rate doubled from 4% to 8% in February.
M|references|| Level | Question | Answer |
M|references||-------|----------|--------|
M|references|| Why 1 | Why did churn double in February? | 60% of churned customers cited "product does not meet needs" in exit surveys. |
M|references|| Why 2 | Why does the product not meet their needs? | These customers were acquired through a January cg targeting a new segment (enterprise) with different requirements. |
M|references|| Why 3 | Why were enterprise customers targeted when the product is built for SMBs? | mkt optimized for signup volume without qualifying for product fit. |
M|references|| Why 4 | Why was there no product-fit qualification? | mkt and product teams do not share a definition of "ideal customer." |
M|references|| Why 5 | Why is there no shared customer definition? | The teams have separate OKRs and do not have a regular alignment process. |
M|references|**Proportional investments:**
M|references|| Level | Investment | Effort | Owner | Deadline |
M|references||-------|-----------|--------|-------|----------|
M|references|| 1 | Reach out to churned enterprise customers; offer refund or alternative solution | 1 day | Customer success | This week |
M|references|| 2 | Pause the enterprise cg until product-fit is assessed | Immediate | mkt lead | Today |
M|references|| 3 | Add lead qualification criteria to cg setup process | 4 hours | mkt ops | This week |
M|references|| 4 | Create shared ideal customer profile (ICP) doc | 1 day | Product + mkt leads | Next 2 weeks |
M|references|| 5 | Establish monthly product-mkt alignment meeting with shared metrics | 2 hours/month | VP Product | Ongoing |
M|references|**Problem:** New collaboration feature launched to 0.5% adoption after 30 days (target was 15%).
M|references|| Level | Question | Answer |
M|references||-------|----------|--------|
M|references|| Why 1 | Why is adoption at 0.5%? | Most users never discovered the feature. Only 8% of users saw the feature announcement. |
M|references|| Why 2 | Why did only 8% see the announcement? | The announcement was an in-app banner that appeared only on first login after release, and 92% of active users did not log in that day. |
M|references|| Why 3 | Why was the announcement limited to a single-day banner? | There is no systematic feature launch process; the team improvised the announcement. |
M|references|| Why 4 | Why is there no feature launch process? | Product and mkt have not collaborated on launches; engineering ships and "hopes people notice." |
M|references|| Why 5 | Why do product and mkt not collaborate on launches? | Launch planning is not part of the product dev workflow. Features are considered "done" when code ships. |
M|references|**Proportional investments:**
M|references|| Level | Investment | Effort | Owner | Deadline |
M|references||-------|-----------|--------|-------|----------|
M|references|| 1 | Create persistent in-app tooltip and email cg for the feature | 1 day | Product + mkt | This week |
M|references|| 2 | Implement multi-touch announcement system (in-app, email, changelog) | 3 days | Product | Next sprint |
M|references|| 3 | Create feature launch checklist template | 4 hours | Product manager | Next week |
M|references|| 4 | Add "launch plan" as required section in feature specs | 2 hours | Product lead | Next week |
M|references|| 5 | Include mkt in sprint planning for launch-relevant features | 1 hour/sprint | Product lead | Ongoing |
M|references|This is the most important aspect of Five Whys in a startup ctx. The investment at each level should be proportional to the problem severity.
M|references|**For a minor issue (first occurrence, low impact):**
M|references|- Level 1: Fix the specific instance (minutes to hours)
M|references|- Level 2: Add a check or guard (hours)
M|references|- Levels 3-5: doc the root cause but do not invest heavily in prevention yet
M|references|**For a major issue (customer-facing, recurring, or high impact):**
M|references|- All levels: Make meaningful investments
M|references|- Level 5: Expect systemic changes (new processes, new tools, organizational changes)
M|references|**For a critical issue (data loss, sec breach, major outage):**
M|references|- All levels: Invest heavily
M|references|- Level 5: May require leadership changes, architecture overhauls, or cultural shifts
M|references|The point is not to boil the ocean on every small problem. It is to make small, incremental investments that compound over time into a robust system.
M|references|Five Whys is most effective when:
M|references|- The problem is specific and observable
M|references|- The people involved are in the room
M|references|- The culture is blame-free
M|references|- The problem is relatively contained (not a vague "culture problem")
M|references|- There is willingness to invest in fixes at every level
M|references|- Follow-up happens (investments are tracked)
M|references|Sometimes each "why" has multiple valid answers, and the chain branches into a tree instead of a line.
M|references|**Solution:** When a branch point occurs, follow the path most likely to lead to a systemic cause. You can explore other branches in separate sessions. Prioritize the branch that feels most within you
M|references|"Why did the database fail?" leads to "Because John wrote bad code."
M|references|**Solution:** Redirect to process: "Why was John in a position to write code that could cause this failure?" This shifts from blame to systems thinking. If a person is the root cause, the actual root 
M|references|Some root causes emerge at "Why 3" and some require "Why 7."
M|references|**Solution:** Five is a guideline, not a rule. Stop when you reach a cause you can address systemically. If you reach "Why 5" and the answer is "because the universe is unfair," you went too far. Back
M|references|"Why did the API fail?" eventually leads to "Because the third-party provider had an outage."
M|references|**Solution:** Redirect to what you can control: "Why did our system fail when the third-party provider had an outage?" This leads to resilience and redundancy investments.
M|references|With more than 6-8 people, Five Whys sessions become unwieldy. Discussions go in circles, and dominant voices take over.
M|references|**Solution:** Keep the group small. Include only people directly involved. Share findings with the broader team afterward.
M|references|- **After every significant incident:** Mandatory Five Whys within 48 hours
M|references|- **Weekly or bi-weekly:** rv outstanding investments from past Five Whys
M|references|- **Monthly:** Look for patterns across multiple Five Whys sessions
M|references|1. **Template the process.** Use a standard doc or tool for every ses.
M|references|2. **Assign a rotating facilitator.** Everyone should practice leading Five Whys.
M|references|3. **Time-box sessions.** 30-45 minutes maximum. If unresolved, schedule a follow-up.
M|references|4. **Track investments.** Use a shared tracker (Jira ticket, Notion database, spreadsheet) for every investment from every ses.
M|references|5. **Celebrate systemic fixes.** When a Five Whys investment prevents a future incident, highlight it publicly.
M|references|```
M|references|FIVE WHYS ses
M|references|=================
M|references|Date: _______________
M|references|Facilitator: _______________
M|references|Participants: _______________
M|references|PROBLEM STATEMENT
M|references|What happened: _______________
M|references|When: _______________
M|references|Impact: _______________
M|references|How it was discovered: _______________
M|references|ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS
M|references|Why 1: _______________
M|references|Why 2: _______________
M|references|Why 3: _______________
M|references|Why 4: _______________
M|references|Why 5: _______________
M|references|PROPORTIONAL INVESTMENTS
M|references|Level 1: _______________  Owner: ___  Deadline: ___
M|references|Level 2: _______________  Owner: ___  Deadline: ___
M|references|Level 3: _______________  Owner: ___  Deadline: ___
M|references|Level 4: _______________  Owner: ___  Deadline: ___
M|references|Level 5: _______________  Owner: ___  Deadline: ___
M|references|FOLLOW-UP
M|references|rv date: _______________
M|references|```
M|references|| Mistake | Consequence | Prevention |
M|references||---------|-------------|------------|
M|references|| Allowing blame language | People become defensive; honesty stops | Establish blame-free ground rules at the start of every ses |
M|references|| Stopping at "Why 1" | Only symptoms get fixed; problems recur | Insist on at least three levels before considering stopping |
M|references|| Accepting vague answers | Root cause remains hidden | Push for specific, verifiable answers at each level |
M|references|| Skipping the investment step | Analysis without action; problems recur | Require at least one investment per level before ending the ses |
M|references|| Not following up | Investments are forgotten; trust erodes | Track investments in a shared system; rv in next ses |
M|references|| Running sessions without affected parties | Analysis is speculative; investments miss the mark | Include the people who were there, not their managers |
M|references|| Combining multiple problems | ses becomes unfocused; no clear root cause | One problem per ses; schedule separate sessions for related problems |
M|references|| Facilitator leading the witness | Answers reflect facilitator's theory, not reality | Facilitator asks questions only; does not suggest answers |
M|references|Five Whys is a practice, not a technique. It improves with repetition. The first few sessions will feel awkward and forced. After a dozen, it becomes the natural rsp to any problem. That shift, from "